CURSORREMOTE — SOURCE-AVAILABLE LICENSE

Copyright (c) 2026 CursorRemote contributors

---

The source is right here. Read it, learn from it, hack on it for yourself.
The validation is a modulo check — we know.

WHAT YOU CAN DO:
- Use this software for anything — personal, commercial, whatever —
  with a valid license key.
- Modify the source for your own use. Go wild.
- Run it on as many of your own machines as you like, as long as each
  concurrent user has their own license key. One key = one seat.

WHAT YOU CAN'T DO:
- Remove, bypass, or disable the license validation and then distribute
  the result. Patching it out for yourself is your business; shipping
  that patch to others is not.
- Redistribute this software (or a derivative) as a product. Don't
  resell it, rebrand it, or wrap it in an installer and charge for
  the software itself. Charging for support, hosting, consulting, or
  a SaaS built on top is fine — the software, as software, stays free.
- Share your license key. Keys are non-transferable.

ONE KEY, ONE SEAT:
Each license key entitles one person to run the software. If your team
has five people using CursorRemote, that's five keys. Site licenses and
volume discounts exist — just ask.

ENFORCEMENT:
We're not going to brick your computer. But if we find a fork circulating
with the license check stripped out, we'll enforce this license to the
extent the law allows. That said — the honor system is still the only
DRM that doesn't ruin computers.

---

Summary: Use it, modify it, keep the license check intact if you
distribute it, one key per person, don't resell the software.
